On its first ocean crossing of 1937, the Hindenburg
carried 36 passengers and 61 crew members. It was
about 7:20 p.m. on May 6, 1937 when the giant ship
approached its berth at Lakehurst, New Jersey. To
the horror of spectators on the ground, there was
suddenly a bright glow near the tail, as the dirigible's
hydrogen fuel burst into flames. Shriveled, bent and
torn, the Hindenburg plummeted to earth, killing 35
people. Public furor in the wake of the accident effec-
tively wrote the end of the era of the commercial
cell and caused the great ship to explode as it made
its approach.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover,
showing
the Hindenburg in flight, was issued by Upper Volta
in 1976. The huge ship traveled between Frankfurt,
Germany and cities in North and South America.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Lakehurst,
New Jersey on May 6, 1984, the exact anniversary of
the disastrous accident involving the Hindenburg.
